A '''bridesman''' is a close male relative and/or friend of the bride, one who walks down the aisle in the bridal ceremony in the traditional place of a [[bridesmaid]].

The term, however, has an ancient and obscure, possibly [[Confabulation|confabulated]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lexic.us/definition-of/bridemen#literary|title=Literary usage of Bridemen |publisher=Lexus.us}}</ref> origin. The term is first noted by the [[Encyclopaedia Judaica]] from the European Jewish Diaspora of the middle of the 13th century. In this context, a bridesman was not a friend of the bride but of the groom. He paid for and arranged the wedding from his own money and would be repaid someday by the groom. It was a position of the highest level of honor in male friendship. It was akin to the modern-day [[best man]]. 

In [[Hungary]], where the word for bridesman is "[[vőfély]]" or sometimes "vőfény" (depending on the region), the ancient tradition of the bridesman is still very popular. The vőfély is the "spokesman" of the bridegroom ("vő" means son-in-law).

