'''Mesaite''' is a very rare mineral with formula CaMn<sup>2+</sup><sub>5</sub>(V<sub>2</sub>O<sub>7</sub>)<sub>3</sub>•12H<sub>2</sub>O. It is monoclinic (space group ''P''2/''n''). It is related to [[fianelite]], another manganese-rich [[divanadate]]. Examples of other divanadate minerals are [[volborthite]], [[engelhauptite]], [[karpenkoite]], and [[martyite]]. <ref>Kampf, A.R., Nash, B.P., Marty, J., and Hughes, J.M., 2015. Mesaite, IMA 2015-069. CNMNC Newsletter No. 28, December 2015, 1861; Mineralogical Magazine 79, 1859–1864</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mindat.org/min-46888.html |title=Mesaite: Mesaite mineral information and data |website=Mindat.org |accessdate=2016-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mindat.org/min-4200.html |title=Volborthite: Volborthite mineral information and data |website=Mindat.org |accessdate=2016-03-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mindat.org/min-43875.html |title=Engelhauptite: Engelhauptite mineral information and data |website=Mindat.org |accessdate=2016-03-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mindat.org/min-46564.html |title=Karpenkoite: Karpenkoite mineral information and data |website=Mindat.org |accessdate=2016-03-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mindat.org/min-32207.html |title=Martyite: Martyite mineral information and data |website=Mindat.org |accessdate=2016-03-08}}</ref>
